Create and Send Authentication Requests in Messaging Sessions

This article applies to enhanced Apple Messages for Business channels, as well as other messaging channels that support authentication. To authenticate users with one of Salesforce's standard authentication providers or a custom provider, follow these steps:

Step 1: Prepare for Authentication

Configure the app you'll use for authentication, create an Apex class, add your authentication provider in Setup, and update your settings in Apple Business Register.

Step 2: Create an Authentication Messaging Component

Create an authentication messaging component that agents can use to verify customers' identity in messaging sessions. To do this:

Go to the Messaging Components page in Setup.
Click New Component.
Select Authentication and follow the prompts to configure the component.
Add a name and description for your component, which is visible only to agents.

Step 3: Send an Authentication Request in a Messaging Session

To send an authentication request during a messaging session:

Click the messaging component action in the messaging window.
Select the authentication component you created and click Insert.
The customer clicks the component link and enters their login credentials.
If the credentials are correct, the agent sees an Authentication successful message; if incorrect, an Authentication denied message.

You can give the customer a second chance by sending the authentication component again.
title: Creating Authentication Requests in Service Cloud Messaging
